helpdesk-ticket.subject: Re: [#INC-2046] Need map new audio computers drive to network.
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Tom and Matt, The O: drive access is associated to the logged-in user. Sam joined the device to the domain, so when you log into the new server, you should get your own O: drive mappings. We checked A&B studio accounts and they do not appear to have any O: drive access. Let me approach this from the other side: With what user do you intend to access the new computer? What folder access on the O: drive are you expecting to see? You have a number of older generic accounts, such as A&B studio. With the current method of ID creation and management, the licensing of software, and access to school features, we're no longer able to create generic user accounts with access to school resources. Let us know how what access the server needs and we'll find a way to provide it. Thanks Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2046 Need map new audio computers drive to network on a new audio serving computer in our main studio. Need Access to the O drive.
Tom Crawford WMSE Krueger Hall x7247

The access should remain the same as the "A-Studio" user account if possible, please. Also, if approved, this new user account should be added to the local administrator groups for two PC's; StudioA & StudioB.
Thank you.
Matt Rockwell

Let us know how what access the server needs and we'll find a way to provide it.

Follow You Printing from Mac 10.9 or newer
By Tony Cottrill, Thu, 24 Sep at 1:12 pm Permanent
Mac OS 10.11 (El Capitan), 10.10 (Yosemite), 10.9 (Mavericks)
Requirements
• Printers hosted and shared from a Windows or Linux server.
• Each user has a domain account and password.
• Running Mac OS X 10.9 or higher. (10.8 may work but not confirmed yet)
Setting up the printers:
1. Navigate to System Preferences -> Print and Scan.
2. Click the + button to add a new printer.
3. Control-Click on the Toolbar and select Customize Toolbar.... Drag the Advanced icon onto the bar, then click the newly added Advanced button
4. Select the Windows printer via spoolss device type.
5. Enter a Device URL
Mac OS 10.9, 10.10, and 10.11 are confirmed to work with the syntax as follows, this may work with all OS’es that define the printer type as “Windows printer via spoolss”. Make sure that there are no spaces after the syntax if you copy and paste from this document. Refer to Figure 1.
smb://printers.msoe.edu/FollowYouPrinting
6. Name field will automatically fill with “printers.msoe.edu” if it recognizes the syntax
7. Choose a driver for this printer by pulling down the drop-down box and selecting Generic PCL Printer.
8. Click the Add button.
9. Open a document and print. Select “printers.msoe.edu” as the printer.
When you go to print it will require authorization that can be saved to the “keychain” which should allow printing with one click once it is saved. Users will need to enter their domain UN and PW. By saving this to the “keychain” you will have to manually update it every time you change your domain UN and PW.
10. You can always see the local status of the print queue by double clicking on the printer in the Print and Scan menu.
[http://cdn.freshservice.com/data/helpdesk/attachments/production/1001321953/original/macprinter.png?1443103641]
Figure 1. Connecting the printers to Mac OS X

Follow You Printing from Mac 10.9 or newer
By Tony Cottrill, Thu, 24 Sep at 1:12 pm Permanent
Mac OS 10.11 (El Capitan), 10.10 (Yosemite), 10.9 (Mavericks)
Requirements
· Printers hosted and shared from a Windows or Linux server.
· Each user has a domain account and password.
· Running Mac OS X 10.9 or higher. (10.8 may work but not confirmed yet) 
 
Setting up the printers:
1. Navigate to System Preferences -> Print and Scan.
2. Click the + button to add a new printer.
3. Control-Click on the Toolbar and select Customize Toolbar.... Drag the Advanced icon onto the bar, then click the newly added Advanced button
4. Select the Windows printer via spoolss device type.
5. Enter a Device URL 
Mac OS 10.9, 10.10, and 10.11 are confirmed to work with the syntax as follows, this may work with all OS’es that define the printer type as “Windows printer via spoolss”. Make sure that there are no spaces after the syntax if you copy and paste from this document. Refer to Figure 1.
smb://printers.msoe.edu/FollowYouPrinting
6.  Name field will automatically fill with “printers.msoe.edu” if it recognizes the syntax
7. Choose a driver for this printer by pulling down the drop-down box and selecting Generic PCL Printer.
8. Click the Add button.
9. Open a document and print. Select “printers.msoe.edu” as the printer.
When you go to print it will require authorization that can be saved to the “keychain” which should allow printing with one click once it is saved. Users will need to enter their domain UN and PW. By saving this to the “keychain” you will have to manually update it every time you change your domain UN and PW.
10. You can always see the local status of the print queue by double clicking on the printer in the Print and Scan menu.
 
Figure 1. Connecting the printers to Mac OS X

helpdesk-note.body:
OS X Yosemite: Printing troubleshooting
If you’re having trouble printing, first try these suggestions:
If your printer is attached to your Mac, make sure it’s firmly connected, plugged into an electrical outlet, and turned on. If you use a printer on the network, make sure your Mac and the printer are still on the same network, the printer is turned on, and the network isn’t experiencing problems. If the network has multiple printers, check which printer you chose—it may be different from the one you think you chose. If you use a shared printer attached to another Mac, make sure the Mac has Mac OS X v10.5 or later, isn’t in sleep, and has sharing turned on. For more information, see Share your printer.
If your printer is attached to your computer’s USB port, open System Information, then click USB. If the printer’s name appears in the hardware list but the printer doesn’t work, review the printer’s documentation for further troubleshooting information or see Check your device’s USB connection.
If you still can’t print, see the additional troubleshooting information below.
Try to resume printing
Click the printer’s icon in the Dock to open the printer’s queue window.
If you see the Resume button in the toolbar, the printer is paused. Click the Resume button. If another job is holding up the queue because of an error, select that job, then click the small Delete Job button on the right (marked with an X). If an individual print job in the list is paused, select it, then click the Resume Job button on the right (marked with a curved arrow).
If you don’t see your print job in the printer’s queue, you may have printed to a different printer. Check the queue windows for other printers, or try printing again, making sure you choose the correct printer. To check the print queue for other printers, choose Apple menu > System Preferences, then click Printers & Scanners. Select a printer in the list, then click Open Print Queue.
Try to print from another app
Try printing from another app, such as TextEdit. If the problem occurs only in one app, review that app’s documentation for further troubleshooting information.
Check the printer
Go to the printer and check the following:
It’s turned on and is displaying normal status lights. It has paper, and the paper isn’t jammed. It has enough ink or toner. Its cables are properly connected.
Add the printer again to create a new printer queue
If the printer is on the network, open Printers & Scanners preferences (choose Apple menu > System Preferences, then click Printers & Scanners). Then, add the printer again to create a new printer queue. If you can print to the newly added printer queue, delete the old printer queue.
If you can’t add the printer because it doesn’t appear in the list of available printers, it may be turned off, or your Mac may be on different network now. If the printer was shared by another user, the user may have stopped sharing it, or the user’s Mac may be offline. If you don’t manage the printer, ask the person who does for help.
Check the network
Open Network Diagnostics, then follow the instructions to make sure you’re connected to the network.
If you’re using a Wi-Fi network and there are multiple Wi-Fi networks available, your Mac and the printer might be on different networks. Open the Wi-Fi menu in the menu bar, then try choosing a different network. To see if the printer you want to use is on the same network as your Mac, open Printers & Scanners preferences (choose Apple menu > System Preferences, then click Printers & Scanners), then click Add . If the printer doesn’t appear in the list of available printers, your Mac might be on a different network. If you know the printer’s IP address (for example, 192.168.1.100), you can try adding it as an IP printer. For more information, see Add or remove a printer. If your printer is connected to a Time Capsule or AirPort base station, disconnect your printer from the Time Capsule or base station, then reconnect it.
Make sure you have the latest software
Make sure you have the correct version of your printer’s software (also called its printer driver).
If you’re using a printer that another user is sharing, make sure you’re both using the same version of the printer software. To find out which version you’re using, open Printers & Scanners preferences (choose Apple menu > System Preferences, then click Printers & Scanners). Select the printer in Printers & Scanners preferences, click Options & Supplies, then click General. Note the driver version. If you’re using a network printer or a printer attached to your Mac, make sure you have the latest version of the software for the printer. If you still have problems, try different printer software for your printer.
If you’re using an AirPrint-enabled printer, you can check with the manufacturer to see if there’s a firmware update for your printer model.
Replace a corrupted printer queue window
If none of the previous solutions work, the printer’s queue may be corrupted. Open Printers & Scanners preferences (choose Apple menu > System Preferences > Printer & Scanner preferences), then delete and set up your printer again. If you still can’t print, reset the printing system.

Hi Serdar,
I found a recent copy of the instructions for the new printer system. I copied the OS10.9 or newer version, but if you have an older OS, I think there is another document too.
Pat
 
Follow You Printing from Mac 10.9 or newer
By Tony Cottrill, Thu, 24 Sep at 1:12 pm Permanent
Mac OS 10.11 (El Capitan), 10.10 (Yosemite), 10.9 (Mavericks)
Requirements
· Printers hosted and shared from a Windows or Linux server.
· Each user has a domain account and password.
· Running Mac OS X 10.9 or higher. (10.8 may work but not confirmed yet) 
 
Setting up the printers:
1. Navigate to System Preferences -> Print and Scan.
2. Click the + button to add a new printer.
3. Control-Click on the Toolbar and select Customize Toolbar.... Drag the Advanced icon onto the bar, then click the newly added Advanced button
4. Select the Windows printer via spoolss device type.
5. Enter a Device URL 
Mac OS 10.9, 10.10, and 10.11 are confirmed to work with the syntax as follows, this may work with all OS’es that define the printer type as “Windows printer via spoolss”. Make sure that there are no spaces after the syntax if you copy and paste from this document. Refer to Figure 1.
smb://printers.msoe.edu/FollowYouPrinting
6.  Name field will automatically fill with “printers.msoe.edu” if it recognizes the syntax
7. Choose a driver for this printer by pulling down the drop-down box and selecting Generic PCL Printer.
8. Click the Add button.
9. Open a document and print. Select “printers.msoe.edu” as the printer.
When you go to print it will require authorization that can be saved to the “keychain” which should allow printing with one click once it is saved. Users will need to enter their domain UN and PW. By saving this to the “keychain” you will have to manually update it every time you change your domain UN and PW.
10. You can always see the local status of the print queue by double clicking on the printer in the Print and Scan menu.
 
Figure 1. Connecting the printers to Mac OS X

helpdesk-ticket.subject: MS Project / Visio
helpdesk-ticket.description:
EE Senior design students need MS Project and MS Visio.
When I (a faculty member) uses "Control Panel\Programs\Get Programs" to install a program from the network, I can see both programs.
However, when students use that same approach, neither program appears in the list of available programs. I have verified this problem with multiple student laptops, both through wireless and hard-wired network connections.
Can you please look into this issue?
Regards, Dr. Prust

helpdesk-note.body:
Dr. Prust,
Unfortunately, to make these products available on Get Programs, we must fully license these products against our current number of enrolled students. While many of the products under MS Office are licensed already, Visio and Project are not included in our current license. The cost to license these products is substantial, and would duplicate our Dreamspark access to the programs.
For the above products, we offer Dreamspark to the students in specific programs, such as EECS. While it may take a while to confirm the license the program, it only needs to be done once, and Dreamspark is already part of the student technology package.
At the current time, unless MS changes their product packaging, we are not looking to fully license any products that are duplicated by another licence or package.

Dr. Prust,
Since it appears a number of accounts with Dreamspark access expired on 10/1/15, I'm attaching this ticket to a Problem Ticket to group them into a single known issue. However, we will need to extend/reactivate the Dreamspark account per user. I have a number of users that have requested an extension via the helpdesk ticketing system. If you have students reporting that they do not have access, please ask them to open a ticket with their MSOE account and we will address them on a per-user basis.
Thanks

helpdesk-note.body:
Dr Prust,
As most accounts had expired on 10/1/15, we enabled verification for all qualified students. Dreamspark will send them an email asking them to verify and reactivate their accounts. If any students did not get this email, have them double-check their email and SPAM folders, or have them open a ticket to the helpdesk including their major and MSOE email address.
In the future, we will be renewing the accounts for the qualified students automatically as we near the expiration date. New students, or students that change majors into an eligible school will need to still request an account directly through the helpdesk.
Marking this and associated issues as resolved.

Mike

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Request for an Extra Stick of Ram
helpdesk-ticket.description: Alice Johnson was wondering if should get buy an extra stick of RAM for her Zbook G1.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: Alice Johnson was wondering if should get buy an extra stick of RAM for her Zbook G1.

helpdesk-note.body:
Good Morning Alice, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2194
You can order RAM for your laptop from Amazon. Here are the specs: DDR3L 1600MHz PC3L-12800 SODIMM RAM These are available from Amazon with a cost of approximately $40 for the 4GB and $80 for the 8GB.
You have one slot free in your Zbook and could purchase either 4GB or 8GB. We can help install this after you have made the purchase or you can install yourself.
I am going to consider this incident as resolved with this information, please call the helpdesk at 414.277.7288 or reply if you feel this is not sufficient..
Peter Pfister Help Desk Coordinator 414.277.7202
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Good Morning Alice,

Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2194

You can order RAM for your laptop from Amazon.  Here are the specs:
DDR3L 1600MHz PC3L-12800 SODIMM RAM
These are available from Amazon with a cost of approximately $40 for the 4GB and $80 for the 8GB.

You have one slot free in your Zbook and could purchase either 4GB or 8GB.  We can help install this after you have made the purchase or you can install yourself.

I am going to consider this incident as resolved with this information, please call the helpdesk at 414.277.7288 or reply if you feel this is not sufficient..

Peter Pfister
Help Desk Coordinator

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Office 2013 not able to update password
helpdesk-ticket.description: After updating my password, Outlook 2013 is unable to connect. I am still able to receive email to my Outlook 365 and my iPhone; however, Outlook 2013 won't connect and doesn't appear to allow me to update the password manually under Account Settings. Please advise. Thanks. -Chris Brook
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
After updating my password, Outlook 2013 is unable to connect. I am still able to receive email to my Outlook 365 and my iPhone; however, Outlook 2013 won't connect and doesn't appear to allow me to update the password manually under Account Settings. Please advise. Thanks.

-Chris Brook

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Christopher Brook,
You probably need to remove your Outlook credentials from the Credential Manager. What happens when you check the "Remember Me" box when signing into Outlook is that Outlook stores those credentials you entered into a program called "Credential Manager". When you change your MSOE account password, which changes your email password, the Credential Manager isn't affected, so Outlook will keep trying to use the old credentials that you told it to remember. We can easily remove these old credentials which will force Outlook to ask for your new credentials the next time you open it.
1. Open the start menu and type "Credential Manager" into the search bar. Open the Credential Manager when it appears as an option.
2. The Credential Manager window should be onscreen. Near the bottom should be a section labeled "Generic Credentials" which should contain an entry labeled something along the lines of "MS.Outlook.youremailaddress". Click on that entry to expand it and choose the option "Remove from Vault". When the warning message appears, click "Yes".
3. Close the Credential Manager. Close Outlook if it is not already closed. Reopen Outlook and it should prompt you for your new password. Feel free to check "Remember Me" again. Just be aware that if you do, you will have to clear the Credential Manager again when you change your password.
Let me know if this solves the issue! Thanks for contacting the IT Helpdesk! Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2227 After updating my password, Outlook 2013 is unable to connect. I am still able to receive email to my Outlook 365 and my iPhone; however, Outlook 2013 won't connect and doesn't appear to allow me to update the password manually under Account Settings. Please advise. Thanks.
-Chris Brook

We can easily remove these old credentials which will force Outlook to ask for your new credentials the next time you open it.

1. Open the start menu and type "Credential Manager" into the search bar. Open the Credential Manager when it appears as an option.

2. The Credential Manager window should be onscreen. Near the bottom should be a section labeled "Generic Credentials" which should contain an entry labeled something along the lines of "MS.Outlook.youremailaddress". Click on that entry to expand it and choose the option "Remove from Vault". When the warning message appears, click "Yes".

3. Close the Credential Manager. Close Outlook if it is not already closed. Reopen Outlook and it should prompt you for your new password. Feel free to check "Remember Me" again. Just be aware that if you do, you will have to clear the Credential Manager again when you change your password.

Let me know if this solves the issue! Thanks for contacting the IT Helpdesk!

Jen“

Joern

helpdesk-ticket.subject: AV Request for two events sponsored by the Center for BioMolecular Modeling
helpdesk-ticket.description:
To Whom it May Concern:
On Saturday, November 7th, the local SMART teams will be taking their Qualification Examination in the Multipurpose Room on the third floor of the CC building. We will need to have access to a screen, the projector and a microphone (of some sort). Would it be possible to set up a time to go over the proper use of the equipment prior to November 7th? I would probably start crying in front of 175 students and teachers, if I broke something!!!!
On Saturday, November 21st, the local SMART Teams will be matched with their research mentor for the duration of the program. We will again be in the Multipurpose Room on the third floor of the CC building. Once again we will need to have access to a screen, the projector and two microphones (the research scientists will be sharing some information with each of the teams - in addition to myself, the researchers will also need access to some sort of amplification - many of them are very soft spoken).
Any assistance you could provide would be greatly appreciated! Thanks - I look forward to hearing from you.
Please don't hesitate to contact me if you need any further information.
Best regards, Gina R. Vogt Program Director MSOE Center for BioMolecular Modeling 414-277-2527

Kevin,
This is a dupe of an email that Micahel responded to earlier: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2212
However, the solution he provided wasn't ideal. We need Heather to connect to MSOE via VPN (https://sslvpn.msoe.edu) so that she has access to the internal KMS licensing server. Once she's connected to out network via VPN and opens MS Office, it will search for and find our KMS server and automatically license the software for another 30 days.
Keep in mind, the remote licences are only valid for 30 days outside of our network, for obvious reasons. If she is not on-campus or using VPN at least once every 30 days, the license will expire.
Hope this helps

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Heather Paar,
It was just brought to my attention that this is the same issue as a ticket from a day ago. The reason that Microsoft Office is not activated is that the way the MSOE key is set up is that you must contact the network once every 30 days in order to keep everything activated. This can be done by connecting to the MSOE network via the GlobalProtect VPN service. Instructions to download, install, and connect to the VPN are available here: http://www.msoe.edu/docs/DOC-1889
After connecting to the VPN please open any Microsoft Office application and the license should renew.
Let me know if this fixes the problem for oyu. Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2245

helpdesk-note.body:
I'm not even sure how to address this. I could start by asking what device the student is using, or where the wireless is spotty. However, I can tell by volume and traffic that - in a general sense - the wireless in the basement, in academic and group areas, is not spotty. I'd need more information to even begin to look into this issue: Time of day, area of complaint, etc. After the fact, and stating that it's been this way the whole year would suggest an individual user problem.
I'd recommend following up with the student at a Tier 1 or Tier 2 level and troubleshooting or gathering more data for me to investigate.

helpdesk-note.body: I called and spoke with Jenny Wraalstedt in the student accounts office. She checked some access logs and noticed some inconsistencies with Ian's access. If the card checks out than this is most likely an issue for Billy Fyfe to check into for door access and Jason for the card readers. I will follow up with Ian tomorrow morning.

Hi Vivian and Dr. Rizza,
AVI systems (AV company) came in today to evaluate the issues in S136. The projectors are a newer model that allows connections to all newer computers, but because it is also closer to the screen, there is not much we can do to move the projection higher. So their recommendation is to remove items "in the way", like the doc camera.
I just saw Dr. Rizza in the hallway, and discussed the possibility of adding a shelf to put the document camera a bit lower and thus out of the line of site for the screen.
I've left the shelf in Vivian's office, and she will put in a maintenance ticket to have this mounted. I will close the AV ticket at this time. helpdesk-note.body:
Dr. Barnicki,
The student licences for MS Office do not include MS Project. However, these licenses are available to students of departments that purchased access to DreamSpark. Students in the EECS or CAECM majors, or in the RSOB department will have DreamSpark access and will be able to download and install MS Project. We recently reissued access to these groups as it had expired on Oct 1.
Currently, we do not have plans to add licenses for MS Project to our MS Office license for all students. If this is something you believe will see regular use over the coming budget years, we should discuss acquiring DreamSpark licenses for departments and majors that will require it. There's is a substantial cost savings in using DreamSpark over issuing a student license for MS Project and MS Visio.
Thanks

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi polancofernandezj, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2325 The MSOE network hard drive disappear from my laptop, so now I can't use any of the software I need to do my homework.
Are the network drives in question the drive letter O or M drives? If so are they disconnected with a red X or are they not showing up on the page at all? I encourage you to try restarting the computer if you have not already. If that doesn't resolve the issue I would recommend that you bring the machine into the CC helpdesk so we can assist you hands on with restoring access to MSOE network resources.
Have a nice day.
Thanks, MSOE Information Technology Cameron Wilson 414-277-7288 helpdesk@msoe.edu

Hello,
I am letting you know that the SAP2000-License Fix still does not work, but there is a procedure to fix the license issue. It is as follows:
1)Go to the Advanced System Setting
2)Create a new Environmental Variable named LSFORCEHOST with a value of applicense2.msoe.edu
Thanks,
Tom Dienhart

Have a great day!

helpdesk-note.body:
Hello Peter,
https://sslvpn.msoe.edu is the site you would go to to download the VPN client. Log in with your MSOE username and password and wait until the page lists the different .exe files it has (The loading screen asks you to click to go back to the login page, don't do that.) Select Windows 7 64 bit and run the install. It will take some time for it to first connect when you try to send your credentials in the program but be persistent and patient.
If there is anything else you need please let us know.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Havilah Normington, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2387
Page Number options in Word will not load. Only the find ones on Microsoft Online option is there.
It sounds like a reinstall of Microsoft Office might solve your problems. If you follow the steps below they should guide you through the reinstall. Note that you either need to be on campus or have global protect running in order for these instructions to work. However, if you would prefer us to handle the reinstall, we would be mroe than happy to if you wanted to stop by the IT Helpdesk located in the CC on the 3rd floor. Please let us know if this solves your problem.
Step 1. Open the start menu and select control panel. Step 2. Select uninstall a program Step 3. Double click on Microsoft Office Step 4. Select Uninstall from the options that pop up. Step 5. Open the control panel and select get programs Step 6 Select Microsoft Office and Click Install Thanks, Thomas Schleich helpdesk@msoe.edu 414-277-7288

helpdesk-note.body:
Hello,
6763 is an 800 number we own and therefor cannot be routed as a persons telephone number. I have changed David's number to x7312. 6763 didn't have voicemail either so he now has a voicemail box linked to his email. To setup the voicemail you can hit the envelope icon on the phone and use the pin 124578 and the system will walk you through setting up a greeting if you wish.
Sorry for the trouble, looks like this problem has existed since we were on the nortel and has just persisted since then, but it should now be resolved completely.
If you have any other phone issues let me know.
Tony x7407

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Time Out Limit on MyMSOE
helpdesk-ticket.description:
From: Gonwa, Dr. William <gonwa@msoe.edu> Sent: Wednesday, October 28, 2015 11:13 AM Subject: Time-Out for MyMSOE To: diFilipo, Stephen <difilipo@msoe.edu>
Stephen:
When I am advising students, I set aside 15 minute blocks. I typically check the student's records as each student arrives. I have an issue with the duration of the MyMSOE timeout. The timeout duration seems shorter than 15 minutes. This requires me to log into MyMSOE (or hit the button that asks me to stay logged in) each time I have a new advisee, even if they arrive back-to-back.
Could the duration before timeout be increased to facilitate advising?
Regards,
Prof. Gonwa
